          "body": "The structure of the cupbearer's dream (40:9-11) and the baker's dream (40:16-17) is carefully parallel. Both dreams occur the same night (40:5). Both feature three units (branches, baskets). Both involve food presented to Pharaoh. Both receive the same timeframe ('within three more days'). The parallelism is the chapter's literary spine. But the outcomes could not be more different: the cupbearer's grapes become wine in Pharaoh's cup (restoration, 40:11-13); the baker's food is consumed by birds before it reaches Pharaoh (death, 40:17-19). The hinge detail is who reaches Pharaoh's hand. In the cupbearer's dream, the cup reaches Pharaoh's hand through the cupbearer's service (40:11). In the baker's dream, the food never reaches Pharaoh — birds intercept it (40:17). Potiphar's house and the prison both taught Joseph to read character, but God gives him the ability to read dreams — to see what the dream says about the dreamer's relation to the sovereign who holds their fate. The baker's impulse to share his dream only after hearing the favorable interpretation (40:16) is itself a character note: he is hoping for the same result, not asking for the truth."
