          "body": "Verses 14-15 are Joseph's most vulnerable moment in the chapter. He has just given the cupbearer life-restoring news; he now asks for one thing in return. The word he uses — *chesed* (40:14) — is the covenant-love word, the term the Old Testament uses for God's faithful loyalty to His people (Exodus 34:6-7; Psalm 136). Joseph asks the cupbearer to show him *chesed*: remember me to Pharaoh; get me out of this house. His stated grounds are innocence: he was kidnapped, not convicted (40:15). There is no self-pity in the appeal — it is a direct, legally framed request. But the word *chesed* carries enormous weight. By invoking it, Joseph is asking for something covenantal: loyalty in return for service, memory in return for gift. The chapter's closing verse answers the appeal: 'yet the chief cupbearer did not remember Joseph, but forgot him' (40:23). The *chesed* Joseph asked of a man was not given by a man. It would be given by God — but not for two more years, and not through the cupbearer's goodwill. The failure of human *chesed* makes room for the fullness of divine *chesed*."
