          "body": "Verses 20-22 are the chapter's moment of vindication. On the third day — Pharaoh's birthday — the feast occurs, the heads are lifted up, and both prophecies execute precisely (40:20-22). The narrator underlines it: 'just as Joseph had interpreted to them' (40:22). Joseph's word was God's word, and God's word was accurate to the calendar. Then verse 23 arrives like a door slamming: 'Yet the chief cupbearer did not remember Joseph, but forgot him.' The juxtaposition is almost cruel. The chapter that confirmed Joseph's prophetic gift ends with the prophet languishing in prison, unremembered. Howard Hendricks observed that the Bible does not resolve every tension at the chapter level — it trusts the reader to keep reading (Howard Hendricks, *Living By the Book*, 1991). Genesis 41:1 reveals the price of the cupbearer's forgetfulness: 'two full years.' Two years in which Joseph had no visible advocate, no changing circumstance, no sign that God had heard. The chapter thus refuses to let God's precision in the two officials' fates be confused with immediacy in Joseph's own deliverance. God can be exact about Pharaoh's servants and still make His own servant wait. The waiting is not abandonment; it is the gap between promise and fulfillment that every biblical saint navigates, from Joseph's pit to the disciples in the upper room to John on Patmos. The cupbearer's forgetfulness is Providence's way of ensuring that when Joseph finally stands before Pharaoh, no one will be able to claim that a palace official opened the door. God alone will have opened it."
