        "title": "Interpretations belong to God — the deflection that is a declaration",
        "range": "40:5-8",
        "excerpt": "Do not interpretations belong to God? Tell it to me, please.",
        "body": "The simultaneous dreaming of verse 5 is the chapter's first overt marker of divine orchestration. The narrator notes that each man had 'his own dream and each dream with its own interpretation' (*pitron*) — before any human interpretation has been offered. The dreams arrived pre-loaded with meaning; the question is only who can unlock it. The officials' distress (40:6) is not vague anxiety — it is the specific anguish of men who know they have received significant communication and cannot decode it. In ancient Near Eastern culture, royal dreams were treated as divine oracles requiring professional interpretation. The absence of the royal dream-interpreters — the *chartummim* who will fail Pharaoh in 41:8 — is what makes the officials' situation so desperate: they are in prison, cut off from the very specialists the Egyptian court employed for exactly this purpose.\n\nJoseph's question — 'Do not interpretations belong to God?' (40:8) — is the chapter's theological summit. It is a rhetorical question expecting the answer 'yes,' but it functions as a declaration: God owns the interpretive enterprise entirely. This is not the posture of a man selling a service; it is the posture of a man who has spent years in the dungeon learning the difference between what he can do and what God does. The deflection to God is also an invitation: if interpretations are God's, and if I am a man through whom God speaks, then tell me your dreams and God will speak.\n\nThe phrase 'tell it to me, please' (*saphar-na*) is gentle and urgent at once. Joseph does not wait for the officials to ask him — he volunteers. This is not opportunism; it is the ministry of a man who genuinely cares that distressed people find an answer. He noticed their faces were sad before he knew they had dreams (40:6-7). The sequence matters: pastoral attentiveness came before prophetic occasion.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pitron* (interpretation, 40:5, 8, 12, 18) appears in the OT almost exclusively in the Joseph narrative — it is a specialized term for the decoded meaning of a divinely sent dream. *Patar* (to interpret, 40:8, 16, 22) is similarly concentrated here. The vocabulary cluster signals that Genesis 40-41 is the OT's fullest treatment of the theology of prophetic dream-interpretation."
